SIMPLE: erupt
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: erupt
<hw>e*rupt"</hw> <pr>(⟦esl⟧*r⟦ucr⟧pt")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>eruption</er>.]</ety> <def>To cause to burst forth; to eject;
<as>as, to <ex>erupt</ex> lava</as>.</def> <rj><au>Huxley.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>erupt</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: erupt
<hw>e*rupt"</hw> <pr>(⟦esl⟧*r⟦ucr⟧pt")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[See
<er>eruption</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To eject something, esp.
lava, water, etc., as a volcano or geyser; <as>as, when Mount Saint
Helens <ex>erupted</ex>, some people were taken by
surprise</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To burst forth; to break out, as ashes from a
volcano, teeth through the gums, etc.; <as>as, the third molar
<ex>erupts</ex> late in most people, and in some persons does not occur
at all.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>When the amount and power of the steam is equal to the demand, it
<qex>erupts</qex> with violence through the lava flood and gives us a
small volcano.</q> <rj><qau>H. J. W. Dam.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>erupting</ent>⟦br⟧
